= Teaching Statement

My aspiration as an educator at California State University, Long Beach is to make the powerful framework of economics accessible and applicable to a diverse student body, including those from low socio-economic and first-generation backgrounds. My teaching philosophy is grounded in translating complex economic theories into clear, intuitive concepts while fostering learning through active engagement. Recognizing CSULB’s commitment to diversity and social impact, I emphasize clarity by bridging formal economic language with everyday intuition, enabling all students to connect theoretical principles with real-world issues, particularly in applied microeconomics and environmental economics.

I employ experiential learning techniques, dedicating class time to workshops where students apply economic tools to analyze contemporary problems, including environmental justice and climate adaptation challenges pertinent to our region. This approach aligns with the department’s focus on interdisciplinary collaboration and equips students with practical skills that extend beyond the classroom. Encouraging a supportive and inclusive learning environment, I use low-stakes activities to build confidence and promote inquiry, which has been shown to enhance both comprehension and engagement.

Teaching at CSULB also entails commitment to mentoring and supporting students from diverse backgrounds. Drawing from my experience working with varied student populations, I am dedicated to empowering learners to overcome barriers and excel academically. Ultimately, my goal is to transform economics into a dynamic toolkit, equipping students with analytical abilities to understand and address pressing societal and environmental challenges. This philosophy resonates deeply with the department’s mission and prepares students for meaningful contributions in their communities and professions.
